<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-025-045 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 575 722</DOCID><JOURNAL>T H E Journal (Technological Horizons In Education)  Nov 1991 v19n4 p73(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber optic LANs link Texas K-12 districts. (WhitehouseIndependent and Glen Rose Independent school districts acquirelocal area networks from Contel of Texas Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Yarborough, Martin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Contel of Texas Inc installed successful fiber-optic local areanetworks (LANs) in the Whitehouse Independent (Whitehouse, TX) andGlen Rose Independent (Glen Rose, TX) K-12 school districts.andP;  Thecompany wanted to encourage its rural customers to use more of thecompany's high-technology communications services.andP;  The pilotWhitehouse system employs fiber-optic cable to link 92 IBMPC-compatibles, 20 Macintoshes, eight 3Com file servers, three IBMPS/2 Model 80 file servers and a IBM PS/2 Model 60 file serverdistributed among six schools via an 10M-bit/second Ethernet LANthrough Contel's central office.andP;  The system handles all studentrecords and scheduling, electronic mail, district financialapplications and food services data.andP;  The Glen Rose system linksabout 250 microcomputers spread through 40 elementary, middle andhigh school classrooms, plus computer labs, libraries andadministrative offices.andP;  What was learned in the Whitehouse trialand future plans for the Glen Rose network are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Contel of Texas Inc. (Contracts).andO;Ticker:    CTC.andO;Topic:     Local Area NetworksElementary SchoolsSecondary SchoolsSystem DevelopmentImplementationComputer Systems IntegratorsFiber OpticsSystem DesignWhitehouse Independent School DistrictGlen Rose Independent School District.andO;Feature:   illustrationmap.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>